WEBVTT

00:00.007 --> 00:01.628
<i>Hi, I'm Chuck.</i>
<i>Here are a few things that</i>

00:01.653 --> 00:02.348
<i>you might need to know.</i>

00:02.349 --> 00:05.425
Come on. Carmichael Industries.
The independence and freedom

00:05.426 --> 00:06.960
to do what we want when we want.

00:06.994 --> 00:07.994
I had no idea I had

00:08.028 --> 00:09.062
<i>such strong feelings for him.</i>

00:09.096 --> 00:10.163
I have to disappear for a while.

00:10.198 --> 00:11.898
All members of
Carmichael Industries

00:11.933 --> 00:15.168
have a position
open to them at the CIA.

00:15.203 --> 00:17.637
If we go back, it's just
gonna be missions and secrets.

00:17.672 --> 00:18.738
I don't want to go back.

00:18.773 --> 00:19.639
Okay.

00:19.674 --> 00:21.508
All we need is each other.

00:23.000 --> 00:29.074
-= www.OpenSubtitles.org =-

00:33.654 --> 00:35.355
So, Mr. Carmichael,

00:35.389 --> 00:38.358
tell me,

00:38.392 --> 00:40.927
how do you feel like
dying today?

00:42.964 --> 00:44.531
Honestly?
You're gonna make me decide?

00:44.565 --> 00:47.667
I find it says
a lot about a man.

00:47.702 --> 00:48.735
I-I, you know, I don't know.

00:48.753 --> 00:49.769
Can't you just pick something?

00:49.804 --> 00:51.338
I've got a lot
on my plate right now.

00:51.372 --> 00:52.739
Like what?

00:52.757 --> 00:54.374
Running your
own company.

00:54.408 --> 00:56.443
It's just, you know, there's
a lot of responsibility

00:56.477 --> 00:58.278
that comes with that.

00:58.312 --> 01:00.847
Not that I don't care
about recovering

01:00.881 --> 01:02.915
spent nuclear fuel
rods, 'cause I do,

01:02.934 --> 01:04.918
but you got to keep your
eye the bottom line.

01:04.952 --> 01:07.604
And with missions, the
bottom line is cash, man.

01:07.638 --> 01:09.222
You know,
with all these

01:09.256 --> 01:10.991
private security firms
out there,

01:11.025 --> 01:13.944
I-I think maybe I'm coming
at this the wrong way.

01:13.978 --> 01:16.129
Maybe Carmichael Industries
needs a new hook, you know?

01:16.163 --> 01:17.731
Almost there, Chuck.

01:17.765 --> 01:19.633
You're very good at talking.

01:19.667 --> 01:21.401
Exactly.

01:21.435 --> 01:22.902
Any spy can sneak
into a building

01:22.937 --> 01:24.904
and-and snap
a few necks.

01:24.939 --> 01:27.107
But what are we doing right
here, right now, the two of us?

01:27.141 --> 01:29.109
We're talking about our
hopes and our dreams.

01:29.143 --> 01:32.078
So you're spies that care?

01:34.115 --> 01:35.448
You're a genius.

01:35.483 --> 01:36.683
That's inspired.
I'm gonna use that.

01:36.717 --> 01:37.717
Can I use that?

01:41.973 --> 01:43.556
I'm glad I could help you,
Mr. Carmichael,

01:43.591 --> 01:47.093
but I think I'll start
by cutting out your tongue.

01:47.128 --> 01:48.595
That would be a horrible idea.

01:49.981 --> 01:51.398
I would not want to do that.

01:51.432 --> 01:52.632
Especially with
such a blunt object.

01:52.650 --> 01:54.317
Stop it, baldy!

01:54.352 --> 01:55.902
Oh, my God.

01:55.936 --> 01:57.237
Chuck, are you okay?

01:57.271 --> 01:59.773
I think we just had
a breakthrough, honey.

01:59.807 --> 02:01.941
Do you think it's
okay to touch that

02:01.975 --> 02:02.942
without a radiation suit?

02:02.977 --> 02:04.944
Shouldn't be any worse

02:04.979 --> 02:06.446
than a couple
dozen X-rays.

02:06.480 --> 02:08.330
We'll be fine,
as long as no one's pregnant.

02:09.667 --> 02:10.917
Okay, Casey,

02:10.951 --> 02:12.752
I'm gonna let you take that.
Let's go.

02:23.464 --> 02:25.832
Don't tell me you're
getting sentimental.

02:27.735 --> 02:30.804
"Welcome back, Gertrude.

02:30.838 --> 02:32.339
"Good to see you, Gertrude.

02:32.373 --> 02:34.607
I missed you,
Gertrude."

02:34.642 --> 02:37.877
Just nod your head if you agree
with any of this.

02:37.912 --> 02:40.213
Didn't hear you come in.

02:40.247 --> 02:43.183
That's because
I took off my heels.

02:43.217 --> 02:45.785
Among other things.

02:45.820 --> 02:49.155
I guess you heard you're not
wanted for murder anymore.

02:49.190 --> 02:51.358
Beckman put a lid
on that whole Decker thing.

02:51.392 --> 02:53.059
Turns out, he was just
a patsy, just...

02:58.866 --> 03:02.836
I didn't fly halfway across
the world to be debriefed.

03:02.870 --> 03:03.837
Uh-uh.

03:03.871 --> 03:05.538
That's your job, John.

03:05.573 --> 03:07.707
Mm...

03:27.528 --> 03:29.562
I thought you said
you were coming to bed.

03:29.597 --> 03:33.333
Have you been
up all night long?

03:33.367 --> 03:34.901
That bad guy
got me thinking.

03:34.919 --> 03:37.070
The one who tried
to cut your tongue out?

03:37.104 --> 03:38.905
Our mission statement,
our mission statement.

03:38.923 --> 03:41.541
We spend so much time
focusing on spy missions,

03:41.575 --> 03:43.910
that we've lost sight of
the-the, you know, uh,

03:43.944 --> 03:45.945
"what are we doing,
why are we here" mission.

03:45.980 --> 03:47.213
Are you feeling okay?

03:47.247 --> 03:49.315
I think that pizza
that Morgan left in the fridge

03:49.350 --> 03:50.450
is starting to turn.

03:50.484 --> 03:52.352
I have never thought
more clearly in my life.

03:52.386 --> 03:56.556
Oh, "the things we feel
but do not share."

03:56.590 --> 03:58.558
What can we, Carmichael
Industries, offer our clients

03:58.592 --> 04:00.527
that other
security firms can't? Go.

04:00.561 --> 04:02.896
Discount electronics?

04:02.930 --> 04:04.063
We care, Sarah.

04:04.098 --> 04:05.598
We care.

04:05.633 --> 04:07.200
C-A-R-E.

04:07.234 --> 04:08.451
Clandestine Agents

04:08.486 --> 04:10.203
Relating Emotionally.

04:10.237 --> 04:11.404
Get it?

04:11.439 --> 04:12.822
You hate it.

04:12.873 --> 04:15.475
No, I think
it's very interesting.

04:15.509 --> 04:18.611
I just, uh, I just feel
very queasy suddenly.

04:18.629 --> 04:20.279
Huh.

04:20.314 --> 04:22.315
Maybe the pizza <i>was</i> bad.

04:29.924 --> 04:32.058
Who told you
you could get dressed?

04:33.093 --> 04:35.094
It's a work day, remember?

04:36.831 --> 04:39.265
First of all,
I have something for you.

04:39.299 --> 04:40.433
Hmm?

04:42.136 --> 04:43.503
Open it.

04:47.358 --> 04:49.325
It's a... sweater.

04:49.360 --> 04:51.110
Why's it so soft?

04:51.144 --> 04:53.146
It's cashmere.

04:53.180 --> 04:54.781
Doesn't feel
flame-retardant.

04:54.815 --> 04:59.335
It's the perfect weight for
a winter night in South Beach.

04:59.370 --> 05:01.321
What's in South Beach?

05:01.355 --> 05:03.456
The second part
of your surprise.

05:03.491 --> 05:06.342
You and I are going to Miami

05:06.377 --> 05:09.429
for three nights at the Maya.

05:11.298 --> 05:13.166
In the middle of the week?

05:13.200 --> 05:15.969
I can't just take off
and sun my buns in Miami.

05:16.003 --> 05:17.370
No, no, no.

05:17.404 --> 05:18.438
I have a job.

05:18.472 --> 05:19.606
Two, technically.

05:19.640 --> 05:21.207
Right, right.

05:21.242 --> 05:22.709
I get it.

05:22.743 --> 05:23.943
I'll, uh, call you later.

05:23.978 --> 05:24.944
Okay.

05:24.979 --> 05:26.646
- Good.
- Hey.

05:26.680 --> 05:28.481
Don't forget your new sweater.

05:35.756 --> 05:37.290
Why are we looking at
surveillance footage

05:37.324 --> 05:39.025
from this morning?

05:39.043 --> 05:41.160
I don't know... yet.

05:41.194 --> 05:43.379
Ever since I got
my brain cleaned,

05:43.414 --> 05:45.832
I've had this suspicion
that something's happening

05:45.866 --> 05:47.199
behind the scenes here.

05:47.218 --> 05:49.168
Wait a minute.

05:49.202 --> 05:50.470
Is that...?

05:50.504 --> 05:51.471
Bingo.

05:51.505 --> 05:53.072
John Casey wearing

05:53.107 --> 05:55.041
a deep V-neck
cashmere sweater.

05:55.075 --> 05:57.393
Who are you,
John Casey?

05:57.428 --> 05:59.896
And what's he doing sneaking
around the Buy More hours

05:59.930 --> 06:01.347
before his shift starts?

06:01.381 --> 06:03.900
Maybe he's here
to meet somebody.

06:05.903 --> 06:07.553
Those two.

06:07.571 --> 06:09.355
Of course
they're in on it.

06:09.389 --> 06:11.224
In on what?
They're probably just doing it

06:11.258 --> 06:13.126
in the home theater room
like I do.

06:13.160 --> 06:14.410
Not likely.

06:14.445 --> 06:17.247
I'm gonna need some
three-by-five cards, stat.

06:17.281 --> 06:18.731
Okay.

06:18.766 --> 06:20.266
Stat!

06:24.622 --> 06:26.005
Ooh!

06:26.040 --> 06:29.108
I got to say, I'm grooving
on that deep V, Casey.

06:31.762 --> 06:34.414
What do you got here?

06:34.448 --> 06:37.150
"Clandestine Agents
Relating Emotionally."

06:37.184 --> 06:38.651
CARE?

06:38.686 --> 06:39.819
Mm-hmm.

06:39.853 --> 06:41.521
You really think this is
what our clients want,

06:41.555 --> 06:43.256
private security firm
that holds their hands,

06:43.290 --> 06:45.291
builds their self-esteem,
tells them they're special?

06:45.326 --> 06:48.595
Isn't that what
everyone wants, Casey?

06:48.629 --> 06:50.163
And it's no coincidence
that we booked

06:50.197 --> 06:51.564
our first client in forever,

06:51.599 --> 06:54.067
hours after I put my CARE
statement on our Web site.

06:54.101 --> 06:55.068
We have a Web site?

06:55.102 --> 06:56.102
Who's the client?

06:57.655 --> 07:00.073
Hey.

07:00.107 --> 07:01.908
I told you I
was working.

07:01.942 --> 07:04.410
So am I.

07:04.444 --> 07:06.779
You're the cl--
She's the client?

07:06.797 --> 07:10.450
May I remind you that you have
your own personal security firm.

07:10.484 --> 07:14.220
My personnel are
stretched a bit thin.

07:14.254 --> 07:17.840
Besides, your company
offers a level of service

07:17.891 --> 07:20.593
that other companies
just don't offer.

07:20.627 --> 07:22.478
You care.

07:23.797 --> 07:27.100
And I intend to take
full advantage of that.

07:27.134 --> 07:30.136
See? Mission statement
working already.

